@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{tai}}" grammar="@HI{{tai}}"}}

<body>

<h1>@HI{{tai}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vmasustem{{}}@EM{{@HI{{tai}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{tai}}}} is an auxiliary used with the @HI{{masu}}-stem of a verb to express a desire to do something. It conjugates
as an @HI{{i}}-adjective.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha@KJ{{open*sea^straw*rope}}he@KJ{{going}}kitaidesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I want to go to Okinawa.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
This form is usually used for the first person or, in an interrogative sentence, for the second person.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{gods^door}}de@KJ{{what}}wo@KJ{{buy}}itaidesuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      What do you want to buy in Kobe?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<br/><br/>

When required for the third person, the form used is with <a href="grammar-garu.html">@HI{{garu}}</a> to make @HI{{tagatteiru}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{three^tree}}sanha@KJ{{car}}wo@KJ{{buy}}itagatteiru.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Miki wants to buy a car.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<br/><br/>

Note, however, that @EM{{@HI{{tai}}}} can be used with a third person:
<ol>
<li> with a past tense
<li> in indirect speech
<li> in explanatory situations
<li> in expressions ofconjecture.
</ol>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{tai}}}} can never be used to form an invitation to do something. Instead use a negative question.
</p>

